AGI - The conditions of Slovak Prime Minister Robert Fico are "extremely serious", after being hit five times with firearm by his attacker. The Minister of Defense, Robert Kalinak, reported this at the press conference, correcting information circulated on the media earlier, according to which the operation to which the head of the government had successfully ended and he poured into stable conditions. The minister clarified that "the intervention is still in progress". Sky News reports it. "The situation is bad," Kalinak admitted, recalling that the attacker, immediately arrested, had political motivations. &nbsp;&nbsp; The attack occurred at the end of a government meeting in Hadlova. According to local newspaper Dennik, Fico came out to greet the crowd when gunshots were fired. The premier was transferred to a hospital in Bratislava by helicopter &nbsp;
&nbsp;
<div </div
<h2> &nbsp;</h2>
<h2> The alleged responsible &nbsp;</h2>
According to the Slovak press agency APA and several national and local media, it is Juraj Chintula, a Slovak writer of 71 years living in the city of Levice. At the moment, the motives of the gesture are not known but, as suggested, the path of political reasons is the most difficult and considered by the authorities. "In 2010 he wrote three poetry collections and a novel. Since 2015 he has been a member of the Slovak writers' Association," adds the Slovak daily Pravda. The man would also be known to be a supporter of the opposition party "Slovacchia progressista", says the Slovak press agency. He would have worked as a security officer in the past.
&nbsp;
<div </div
&nbsp;
<h2> The area of the attack
The area in front of the House of Culture in Handlova, where the government meeting was held after which Prime Minister Robert Fico was wounded by gunshots, is currently evacuated. The Slovak agency Tasr reports that the attacker was arrested.
<h2> Parliament session suspended
The Slovak Parliament suspended the sitting in the light of Prime Minister Robert Fico's wound in an attack on gunshots at Handlova. This was announced by Parliament's deputy speaker, Lubos Blaha, cited by the local information site Dennikn.&nbsp; The Slovak President, Zuzana Caputova, "condemned the attack firmly" to the Prime Minister, Robert Fico. The spokesman of Head of State Martin Strizinec, cited by the national media.&nbsp;
&nbsp;
&nbsp;

