AGI - In France it is a neighborhoodless hunt for the authors of the bloody assault on a prison van that cost the life to two agents and allowed the escape of a prisoner. The attack, spectacular and extremely rare in France, was completed in the late morning of yesterday by a commando who spurned with a car the van to the Incarville toll in Normandy before opening fire against the agents. Two guards died and three more were seriously injured. The detainee, in transit to the penitentiary of Evreux after an audience in the court of Rouen, managed to escape with his accomplices. "We have invested a lot of resources to find the escape and the gang that has released it," said Interior Minister Gerald Darmanin on RTL radio.
&nbsp;
The attack, which French President Emmanuel Macron called "slucking", aroused a wave of emotion among the prison guards that this morning protested in front of several penitentiary institutions to ask for more resources. In the face of the wararms of which the commando was equipped, the agents had only " Sig Sauer automatic guns", said the unionist Frederic Liakhoff. The unions, who will be received in the afternoon at the Ministry of Justice, ask in particular "the drastic reduction of translations favouring the use of video conferencing.
&nbsp;
Denouncing a "vile crime", Justice Minister Eric Dupond-Moretti asked for a minute of silence in all jurisdictions and met colleagues of the agents killed. It is the first time since 1992 that a penitentiary agent is killed in the exercise of his duties in France and since yesterday "more than 450 police officers and gendarme" are mobilized "only for the department of Eure", Darmanin explained, citing also means of "international cooperation". Denouncing the "barbaries" of the attack, the minister also pointed his finger against "narcobanditism". The detainee on the run, Mohamed Amra, 30 years old, has already been sentenced thirteen times but "no so far for violation of drug legislation", said the Paris prosecutor Laure Beccuau on Tuesday evening.
&nbsp;
The last sentence dates back to May 7th, commissioned by the Evreux court "for a burglary" which took him 18 months in prison. He was also in precautionary custody for other cases, including drug trafficking in the region of Marseille, the outbreak of narcobanditism in France, and complicity in murder and kidnapping. During his brief detention in Evreux, where he was transferred to April to be tried, he began to sew the bars of his cell. "It's completely incomprehensible, I can't imagine that this boy might be involved" in the commando attack, Amra's lawyer Hugues Vigier answered. This operation "does not match the profile I had perceived of him, if he is involved is because I was really wrong about what he had in his head and what he was capable of", he added.&nbsp;

